Overall Goal
======

In 2021 I would like to deepen my knowledge of macroeconomics, particularly in regards to the labor market. Specifically, I am interested in examining the effects of search frictions in the face of heterogeneous preferences and actions. I would also like to explore the effects of monetary policy on the labor market, particularly in the light of the flattening Phillips curve. Finally, given the massive break in macroeconomic variables in March 2020 for most economies, forecasting techniques for macroeconomic variables require exploitation of non-traditional data, particularly high-frequency data, to understand the current environment. I would enjoy exploring these techniques, particularly in relation to the effects on different industries.

Underemployment
------

Much of the existing work has focused on differences in income, but more should be done in exploring both changing preferences and constraints. For example, I am currently working to develop a model which explains workers who are employed part-time but would prefer a full-time position. This complicates the labor/leisure tradeoff by restricting employment status to three states, rather than the traditional New Keynesian continuous variable of hours worked. Restricting workers to the three labor states of employed, unemployed, and under-employed will better model the labor market decisions of lower-income households, particularly if savings is constrained.

Flattening Phillips Curve
------

Many researchers are focused on this, and honestly I have no particular research plan at the moment. However, as central banks continue to rely more heavily on unconventional monetary policy tools, such as the Federal Reserve's purchase of corporate bonds for the first time. I intend to jump on the Heterogeneous Agent New Keynesian (HANK) Model bus an ride it wherever the research goes, with the occasional contribution along the way.

Novel Methods
------

The COVID-19 pandemic has upended financial markets and changed the weights of variables traditionally used to explain the economy. At the same time, machine learning tools have rapidly started to become mainstream. My interest is in the best way to train these models to adapt to the evolving conditions. Particularly of interest are time-varying variable weighing parameters, as these are necessary to capture the continuing structural changes as lockdown measures and distancing behaviors evolve. Admittedly this is my weakest area, but I suspect that it is also the most ripe for inter-disciplinary study. And we need more cross-department cooperation in this world.
